'''Wilhelm Gause''' (March 27, 1853 - June 13, 1916) was a German-Austrian painter.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wilhelm Gause|url=http://www.mutualart.com/Artist/Wilhelm-Gause/57593F850FFE062F|work=Art Appraisal|publisher=Mutual Art|accessdate=21 May 2014|quote=Several works by the artist have been sold at auction, including 'Party on the Ice' sold at Sotheby's New York 'Old Master & 19th Century European Art' in 2011 for $13,750.}}</ref> He studied at the Düsseldorf Academy, and in 1888 exhibited his work in Vienna.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wilhelm Gause|url=http://www.artbol.com/painting-artist/wilhelm-gause|work=Painting/Artist|publisher=Artbol|accessdate=21 May 2014|quote="Unfortunately, very little is known about this outstanding German artist, whose paintings and drawings consist mainly of genre scenes. Gause studied at the Dusseldorf Academy and exhibited at Vienna in 1888."}}</ref>

==Works==
Perhaps Gause’s most famous work is “Court Ball at the Hofburg.” Created in 1900, it hangs today within the walls of the Wien Museum Karlsplatz, Vienna, Austria.<ref>{{cite web|title=Court Ball at the Hofburg|url=http://www.zazzle.com/court_ball_at_the_hofburg_1900_print-228835849800428486|publisher=Zazzle|accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref> It depicts aristocrats crowding around [[Franz Joseph I of Austria]] at the [[Hofburg Imperial Palace]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Creator:Wilhelm_Gause |title=Creator:Wilhelm Gause - Wikimedia Commons |publisher=Commons.wikimedia.org |date= |accessdate=2014-06-04}}</ref>
[[File:Wilhelm Gause Hofball in Wien.jpg|thumb| ''Court Ball at the Hofburg, 1900'']]

On January 28, 2011, Another painting of his, ''Party on the Ice, 1909'' was sold at [[Sotheby's]] in New York for $13,750.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wilhelm Gause|url=http://www.mutualart.com/Artist/Wilhelm-Gause/57593F850FFE062F|work=Art Appraisal|publisher=Mutual Art|accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref>

